{"name":"Mathlib.Tactic.RCases","instances":[{"typeNames":["Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt"],"name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.instReprRCasesPatt","className":"Repr"},{"typeNames":["Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt"],"name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.instInhabitedRCasesPatt","className":"Inhabited"},{"typeNames":["Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt"],"name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.instToMessageDataRCasesPatt","className":"Lean.ToMessageData"}],"imports":["Init","Lean"],"declarations":[{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L587-L597","name":"Mathlib.Tactic.rintro","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Mathlib.Tactic.rintro","doc":"The `rintro` tactic is a combination of the `intros` tactic with `rcases` to\nallow for destructuring patterns while introducing variables. See `rcases` for\na description of supported patterns. For example, `rintro (a | ⟨b, c⟩) ⟨d, e⟩`\nwill introduce two variables, and then do case splits on both of them producing\ntwo subgoals, one with variables `a d e` and the other with `b c d e`.\n\n`rintro`, unlike `rcases`, also supports the form `(x y : ty)` for introducing\nand type-ascripting multiple variables at once, similar to binders.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L578-L584","name":"Mathlib.Tactic.rintro?","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Mathlib.Tactic.rintro?","doc":"`rintro?` will introduce and case split on variables in the same way as\n`rintro`, but will also print the `rintro` invocation that would have the same\nresult. Like `rcases?`, `rintro? : n` allows for modifying the\ndepth of splitting; the default is 5.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L544-L576","name":"Mathlib.Tactic.obtain","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Mathlib.Tactic.obtain","doc":"The `obtain` tactic is a combination of `have` and `rcases`. See `rcases` for\na description of supported patterns.\n\n```lean\nobtain ⟨patt⟩ : type := proof\n```\nis equivalent to\n```lean\nhave h : type := proof\nrcases h with ⟨patt⟩\n```\n\nIf `⟨patt⟩` is omitted, `rcases` will try to infer the pattern.\n\nIf `type` is omitted, `:= proof` is required.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L493-L534","name":"Mathlib.Tactic.rcases","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Mathlib.Tactic.rcases","doc":"`rcases` is a tactic that will perform `cases` recursively, according to a pattern. It is used to\ndestructure hypotheses or expressions composed of inductive types like `h1 : a ∧ b ∧ c ∨ d` or\n`h2 : ∃ x y, trans_rel R x y`. Usual usage might be `rcases h1 with ⟨ha, hb, hc⟩ | hd` or\n`rcases h2 with ⟨x, y, _ | ⟨z, hxz, hzy⟩⟩` for these examples.\n\nEach element of an `rcases` pattern is matched against a particular local hypothesis (most of which\nare generated during the execution of `rcases` and represent individual elements destructured from\nthe input expression). An `rcases` pattern has the following grammar:\n\n* A name like `x`, which names the active hypothesis as `x`.\n* A blank `_`, which does nothing (letting the automatic naming system used by `cases` name the\n  hypothesis).\n* A hyphen `-`, which clears the active hypothesis and any dependents.\n* The keyword `rfl`, which expects the hypothesis to be `h : a = b`, and calls `subst` on the\n  hypothesis (which has the effect of replacing `b` with `a` everywhere or vice versa).\n* A type ascription `p : ty`, which sets the type of the hypothesis to `ty` and then matches it\n  against `p`. (Of course, `ty` must unify with the actual type of `h` for this to work.)\n* A tuple pattern `⟨p1, p2, p3⟩`, which matches a constructor with many arguments, or a series\n  of nested conjunctions or existentials. For example if the active hypothesis is `a ∧ b ∧ c`,\n  then the conjunction will be destructured, and `p1` will be matched against `a`, `p2` against `b`\n  and so on.\n* An alteration pattern `p1 | p2 | p3`, which matches an inductive type with multiple constructors,\n  or a nested disjunction like `a ∨ b ∨ c`.\n\nA pattern like `⟨a, b, c⟩ | ⟨d, e⟩` will do a split over the inductive datatype,\nnaming the first three parameters of the first constructor as `a,b,c` and the\nfirst two of the second constructor `d,e`. If the list is not as long as the\nnumber of arguments to the constructor or the number of constructors, the\nremaining variables will be automatically named. If there are nested brackets\nsuch as `⟨⟨a⟩, b | c⟩ | d` then these will cause more case splits as necessary.\nIf there are too many arguments, such as `⟨a, b, c⟩` for splitting on\n`∃ x, ∃ y, p x`, then it will be treated as `⟨a, ⟨b, c⟩⟩`, splitting the last\nparameter as necessary.\n\n`rcases` also has special support for quotient types: quotient induction into Prop works like\nmatching on the constructor `quot.mk`.\n\n`rcases h : e with PAT` will do the same as `rcases e with PAT` with the exception that an\nassumption `h : e = PAT` will be added to the context.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L484-L490","name":"Mathlib.Tactic.rcases?","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Mathlib.Tactic.rcases?","doc":"`rcases? e` will perform case splits on `e` in the same way as `rcases e`,\nbut rather than accepting a pattern, it does a maximal cases and prints the\npattern that would produce this case splitting. The default maximum depth is 5,\nbut this can be modified with `rcases? e : n`.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L475-L477","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.rintro","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.rintro","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L467-L470","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.rintroContinue.loop","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.rintroContinue.loop","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L463-L471","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.rintroContinue","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.rintroContinue","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L451-L461","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.rintroCore","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.rintroCore","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L442-L447","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.obtainNone","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.obtainNone","doc":"The `obtain` tactic in the no-target case. Given a type `T`, create a goal `|- T` and\nand pattern match `T` against the given pattern. Returns the list of goals, with the assumed goal\nfirst followed by the goals produced by the pattern match. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L423-L437","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.rcases","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.rcases","doc":"Given a list of targets of the form `e` or `h : e`, and a pattern, match all the targets\nagainst the pattern. Returns the list of produced subgoals. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L408-L419","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.generalizeExceptFVar","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.generalizeExceptFVar","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L392-L405","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.parse","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.parse","doc":"Parses a `Syntax` into the `RCasesPatt` type used by the `RCases` tactic. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L384-L387","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.finish","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.finish","doc":"The terminating continuation used in `rcasesCore` and `rcasesContinue`. We specialize the type\n`α` to `Array MVarId` to collect the list of goals, and given the list of `clears`, it attempts to\nclear them from the goal and adds the goal to the list. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L374-L379","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.tryClearMany'","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.tryClearMany'","doc":"Like `tryClearMany`, but also clears dependent hypotheses if possible "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L360-L369","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.rcasesContinue","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.rcasesContinue","doc":"This will match a list of patterns against a list of hypotheses `e`. The arguments are similar\nto `rcasesCore`, but the patterns and local variables are in `pats`. Because the calls are all\nnested in continuations, later arguments can be matched many times, once per goal produced by\nearlier arguments. For example `⟨a | b, ⟨c, d⟩⟩` performs the `⟨c, d⟩` match twice, once on the\n`a` branch and once on `b`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L345-L352","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.rcasesCore.align","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.rcasesCore.align","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L296-L353","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.rcasesCore","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.rcasesCore","doc":"This will match a pattern `pat` against a local hypothesis `e`.\n* `g`: The initial subgoal\n* `fs`: A running variable substitution, the result of `cases` operations upstream.\n  The variable `e` must be run through this map before locating it in the context of `g`,\n  and the output variable substitutions will be end extensions of this one.\n* `clears`: The list of variables to clear in all subgoals generated from this point on.\n  We defer clear operations because clearing too early can cause `cases` to fail.\n  The actual clearing happens in `RCases.finish`.\n* `e`: a local hypothesis, the scrutinee to match against.\n* `a`: opaque \"user data\" which is passed through all the goal calls at the end.\n* `pat`: the pattern to match against\n* `cont`: A continuation. This is called on every goal generated by the result of the pattern\n  match, with updated values for `g` , `fs`, `clears`, and `a`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L255-L279","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.subst'","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.subst'","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L238-L250","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.processConstructors","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.processConstructors","doc":"Takes a list of constructor names, and an (alternation) list of patterns, and matches each\npattern against its constructor. It returns the list of names that will be passed to `cases`,\nand the list of `(constructor name, patterns)` for each constructor, where `patterns` is the\n(conjunctive) list of patterns to apply to each constructor argument. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L225-L232","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.processConstructor","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.processConstructor","doc":"Takes the number of fields of a single constructor and patterns to match its fields against\n(not necessarily the same number). The returned lists each contain one element per field of the\nconstructor. The `name` is the name which will be used in the top-level `cases` tactic, and the\n`rcases_patt` is the pattern which the field will be matched against by subsequent `cases`\ntactics. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L211-L216","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.instToMessageDataRCasesPatt.fmt","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.instToMessageDataRCasesPatt.fmt","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L209-L210","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.instToMessageDataRCasesPatt.parenAbove","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.instToMessageDataRCasesPatt.parenAbove","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L208-L216","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.instToMessageDataRCasesPatt","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.instToMessageDataRCasesPatt","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L202-L205","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.alts₁","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.alts₁","doc":"This function is used for producing rcases patterns based on a case tree. This is like\n`alts₁Core`, but it produces a cases pattern directly instead of a list of alternatives. We\nspecially translate the empty alternation to `⟨⟩`, and translate `|(a | b)` to `⟨a | b⟩` (because we\ndon't have any syntax for unary alternation). Otherwise we can use the regular merging of\nalternations at the last argument so that `a | b | (c | d)` becomes `a | b | c | d`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L192-L195","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.alts₁Core","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.alts₁Core","doc":"This function is used for producing rcases patterns based on a case tree. Here we are given\nthe list of patterns to apply to each argument of each constructor after the main case, and must\nproduce a list of alternatives with the same effect. This function calls `tuple₁` to make the\nindividual alternatives, and handles merging `[a, b, c | d]` to `a | b | c | d` instead of\n`a | b | (c | d)`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L182-L185","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.tuple₁","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.tuple₁","doc":"This function is used for producing rcases patterns based on a case tree. This is like\n`tuple₁Core` but it produces a pattern instead of a tuple pattern list, converting `[n]` to `n`\ninstead of `⟨n⟩` and `[]` to `_`, and otherwise just converting `[a, b, c]` to `⟨a, b, c⟩`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L173-L177","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.tuple₁Core","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.tuple₁Core","doc":"This function is used for producing rcases patterns based on a case tree. Suppose that we have\na list of patterns `ps` that will match correctly against the branches of the case tree for one\nconstructor. This function will merge tuples at the end of the list, so that `[a, b, ⟨c, d⟩]`\nbecomes `⟨a, b, c, d⟩` instead of `⟨a, b, ⟨c, d⟩⟩`.\n\nWe must be careful to turn `[a, ⟨⟩]` into `⟨a, ⟨⟩⟩` instead of `⟨a⟩` (which will not perform the\nnested match). "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L162-L164","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.alts'","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.alts'","doc":"Convert a list of patterns to an alternation pattern, but mapping `[p]` to `p` instead of\na unary alternation `|p`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L156-L158","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.tuple'","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.tuple'","doc":"Convert a list of patterns to a tuple pattern, but mapping `[p]` to `p` instead of `⟨p⟩`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L151-L153","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.typed?","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.typed?","doc":"Convert a list of patterns to a tuple pattern, but mapping `[p]` to `p` instead of `⟨p⟩`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L146-L148","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.asAlts","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.asAlts","doc":"Interpret an rcases pattern as an alternation, where non-alternations are treated as one\nalternative. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L140-L142","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.asTuple","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.asTuple","doc":"Interpret an rcases pattern as a tuple, where `p` becomes `⟨p⟩`\nif `p` is not already a tuple. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L131-L136","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.ref","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.ref","doc":"Get the syntax node from which this pattern was parsed. Used for error messages "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L122-L128","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.name?","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.name?","doc":"Get the name from a pattern, if provided "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L119-L119","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.instInhabitedRCasesPatt","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt.instInhabitedRCasesPatt","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L115-L115","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.instReprRCasesPatt","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.instReprRCasesPatt","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L109-L115","name":"Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.RCases.RCasesPatt","doc":"An `rcases` pattern can be one of the following, in a nested combination:\n\n* A name like `foo`\n* The special keyword `rfl` (for pattern matching on equality using `subst`)\n* A hyphen `-`, which clears the active hypothesis and any dependents.\n* A type ascription like `pat : ty` (parentheses are optional)\n* A tuple constructor like `⟨p1, p2, p3⟩`\n* An alternation / variant pattern `p1 | p2 | p3`\n\nParentheses can be used for grouping; alternation is higher precedence than type ascription, so\n`p1 | p2 | p3 : ty` means `(p1 | p2 | p3) : ty`.\n\nN-ary alternations are treated as a group, so `p1 | p2 | p3` is not the same as `p1 | (p2 | p3)`,\nand similarly for tuples. However, note that an n-ary alternation or tuple can match an n-ary\nconjunction or disjunction, because if the number of patterns exceeds the number of constructors in\nthe type being destructed, the extra patterns will match on the last element, meaning that\n`p1 | p2 | p3` will act like `p1 | (p2 | p3)` when matching `a1 ∨ a2 ∨ a3`. If matching against a\ntype with 3 constructors,  `p1 | (p2 | p3)` will act like `p1 | (p2 | p3) | _` instead.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L84-L85","name":"Lean.Meta.FVarSubst.append","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Meta.FVarSubst.append","doc":"Constructs a substitution consisting of `s` followed by `t`.\nThis satisfies `(s.append t).apply e = t.apply (s.apply e)` "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L78-L78","name":"«termListΠ»","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#«termListΠ»","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L75-L75","name":"«termListΣ»","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#«termListΣ»","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L70-L70","name":"Lean.Parser.Tactic.rintroPat.binder","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Parser.Tactic.rintroPat.binder","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L69-L69","name":"Lean.Parser.Tactic.rintroPat.one","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Parser.Tactic.rintroPat.one","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L68-L68","name":"Lean.Parser.Tactic.rintroPat.quot","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Parser.Tactic.rintroPat.quot","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L66-L66","name":"Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.paren","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.paren","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L65-L65","name":"Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.tuple","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.tuple","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L64-L64","name":"Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.clear","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.clear","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L63-L63","name":"Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.ignore","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.ignore","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L62-L62","name":"Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.one","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.one","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L61-L61","name":"Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPatLo","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPatLo","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L60-L60","name":"Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPatMed","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPatMed","doc":""},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/876d9cc42ccbfea023752e40e6edb7279d9c6b5a/Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.lean#L59-L59","name":"Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.quot","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/RCases.html#Lean.Parser.Tactic.rcasesPat.quot","doc":""}]}